om my personal experience'''%0a>>messageitem%3c%3c%0aSimilar to you, I speak English and Mandarin too. Although I do not observe a different in math problem solving when I think in Chinese, my native language, I do prefer to think in English for science subjects such as Physics. One other difference I obeserve is that I can formulate a sentence as I speak better in Englsih. I suppose this is partly due to the fact English allows you to add adjectives after nouns. For example you can do "[noun], which is [adj]". This will be quite grammatically awkward in Mandarin. %0a>>%3c%3c%0a#foxend 210204-044015-946770#%0a#foxbegin 210204-030453-513300#%0a(:div1 class=messagehead:)%0a>>rfloat%3c%3c   %0a[-03.02.2021 - 19:04-] &nbsp; %0a>>%3c%3c%0a!!!!!roochis%0a(:div1end:) %0a>>messageitem%3c%3c %0a'''1984'''%0a>>messageitem%3c%3c%0aThis idea is explored in the book 1984! The totalitarian government creates a new restrictive language, and it begs the question can we long for ideas like freedom if there are no words to define that concept to begin with  %0a>>%3c%3c%0a#foxend 210204-030453-513300#%0a#foxbegin 210203-145028-61440#%0a(:div1 class=messagehead:)%0a>>rfloat%3c%3c   %0a[-03.02.2021 - 06:50-] &nbsp; %0a>>%3c%3c%0a!!!!!AlbertL%0a(:div1end:) %0a>>messageitem%3c%3c %0a''''''%0a>>messageitem%3c%3c%0aIf I recall correctly this idea is known as the Sapir-Whorf hypothesis and there is evidence that it does hold in some cases. %0a>>%3c%3c%0a#foxend 210203-145028-61440#%0a%0a%0a%0a(:Section: :)%0a(:Category: PracticeCategory:)
